Aérospatiale SA 330 Puma.label: Aérospatiale SA 330 Puma
Aérospatiale SA 330 Puma.description: The Aérospatiale SA 330 Puma is a four-bladed, twin-engined medium transport/utility helicopter. The Puma was originally manufactured by Sud Aviation of France, and continued to be produced by Aérospatiale. Wikipedia

AEG B.III.label: AEG B.III
AEG B.III.description: The AEG B.III was a German two-seat biplane reconnaissance aircraft produced in very small numbers from 1915. Wikipedia

AEG C.III.label: AEG C.III
AEG C.III.description: The AEG C.III was a two-seat biplane reconnaissance aircraft, a single prototype of which was built during World War I. Wikipedia

AEG C.VII.label: AEG C.VII
AEG C.VII.description: The AEG C.VII was a prototype two-seat biplane reconnaissance aircraft of World War I. It was developed from the C.IV but did not enter production. Wikipedia

AEG C.VIII.label: AEG C.VIII
AEG C.VIII.description: The AEG C.VIII was a prototype two-seat reconnaissance aircraft of World War I. Two examples were built, based on the successful C.IV design, one of biplane configuration, the other a triplane. Wikipedia

Adam A500.label: Adam A500
Adam A500.description: The Adam A500 is an American six-seat civil utility aircraft that was produced by Adam Aircraft Industries. Wikipedia

Adam A700.label: Adam A700
Adam A700.description: The Adam A700 AdamJet was a proposed six-seat civil utility aircraft developed by Adam Aircraft Industries starting in 2003. Wikipedia

Ader Avion III.label: Ader Avion III
Ader Avion III.description: The Avion III was a primitive steam-powered aircraft built by Clément Ader between 1892 and 1897, financed by the French War Office. Wikipedia

AeroVironment RQ-14 Dragon Eye.label: AeroVironment RQ-14 Dragon Eye
AeroVironment RQ-14 Dragon Eye.description: The Dragon Eye Unmanned Aerial Vehicle is a small reconnaissance UAV developed by the Naval Research Laboratory and the Marine Corps Warfighting Laboratory for use by the U.S. Marine Corps. Wikipedia

Aero A.10.label: Aero A.10
Aero A.10.description: The Aero Letňany A.10 was a biplane airliner produced in Czechoslovakia shortly after World War I. It was the first commercial aircraft to be built in Czechoslovakia and was known as the Ae-10 Limousine. Wikipedia

Aero A.100.label: Aero A.100
Aero A.100.description: The Aero A.100 was a biplane light bomber and reconnaissance aircraft built in Czechoslovakia during the 1930s. It was the final step in a design lineage that extended back to the Aero A.11 a decade earlier. Wikipedia

Aero A.102.label: Aero A.102
Aero A.102.description: The Aero A.102 was a Czechoslovakian fighter aircraft that flew in prototype form in 1934. It was developed in response to a Czech Air Force requirement of that year, but was passed over in favour of the Avia B.35. Wikipedia

Aero A.11.label: Aero A.11
Aero A.11.description: The Aero A.11 was a biplane light bomber and reconnaissance aircraft built in Czechoslovakia between the First and Second World Wars. It formed the basis for a large number of other Czechoslovakian military aircraft of the inter-war period. Wikipedia

Aero A.14.label: Aero A.14
Aero A.14.description: The Aero A.14 was a Czechoslovakian biplane military reconnaissance aircraft built in the 1920s. It was essentially a slightly modified version of the Hansa-Brandenburg B.I aircraft that Aero had been ... Wikipedia

Aero A.12.label: Aero A.12
Aero A.12.description: The Aero A.12 was a Czechoslovakian biplane light bomber and military reconnaissance aircraft manufactured in small numbers shortly after World War I. Wikipedia

Aero A.18.label: Aero A.18
Aero A.18.description: The Aero A.18 was a biplane fighter aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in the 1920s. It was a development of the Ae 02 and Ae 04 fighters Aero had designed during World War I, but also borrowed from the more recent A.11 reconnaissance-bomber design. Wikipedia

Aero A.200.label: Aero A.200
Aero A.200.description: The Aero A.200 was a sportsplane of Czechoslovakia, designed and built specifically to compete in Challenge 1934, the European touring plane championships. It was a four-seater low-wing monoplane. Wikipedia

Aero A.204.label: Aero A.204
Aero A.204.description: The Aero A.204 was a Czechoslovakian airliner that flew in prototype form in 1936. It was developed specifically for ČSA, but much to Aero's surprise and disappointment, the national airline selected a British product instead, the Airspeed Envoy. Wikipedia

Aero A.300.label: Aero A.300
Aero A.300.description: The Aero A.300 was a Czechoslovakian bomber aircraft that first flew in 1938 as a much refined development of the A.304. Despite showing much promise, development and production of the aircraft was interrupted by the outbreak of World War II. Wikipedia

Aero A.23.label: Aero A.23
Aero A.23.description: The Aero A.23 was a Czechoslovakian biplane airliner of the 1920s. Aero's previous airliner design, the A.10 had been a relatively crude machine drawing heavily on World War I military aircraft. Wikipedia

Aero A.304.label: Aero A.304
Aero A.304.description: The Aero A.304 was a Czechoslovakian bomber aircraft that first flew in 1937. It had originally been developed as an airliner, the A.204, but when Aero could not find buyers for the design, it was ... Wikipedia

Aero A.32.label: Aero A.32
Aero A.32.description: The Aero A.32 was a biplane built in Czechoslovakia in the late 1920s for army co-operation duties including reconnaissance and tactical bombing. Wikipedia

Aero A.35.label: Aero A.35
Aero A.35.description: The Aero A.35 was a Czechoslovakian airliner of the 1920s and 30s. Designed for long-range flight, with a transatlantic crossing in mind, it saw service with CSA although no such crossing was ever attempted. Wikipedia

Aero A.38.label: Aero A.38
Aero A.38.description: The Aero A.38 was a Czechoslovakian biplane airliner of the 1920s and 30s. Following the relatively modern A.35, this aircraft was something of a throwback, marrying a fuselage derived from the A.35 to wings copied from the A.23. Wikipedia

Aero A.42.label: Aero A.42
Aero A.42.description: The Aero A.42 was a Czechoslovakian bomber aircraft of 1929 that was only ever produced in prototype form. For its day, it was an advanced design, with a sleek monoplane configuration. Wikipedia

Aero Ae 01.label: Aero Ae 01
Aero Ae 01.description: The Aero Ae 01 was a Czechoslovakian military trainer biplane built in 1919, the company's first attempt to modify one of the aircraft designs they had been manufacturing under licence during World War I, the Hansa-Brandenburg B.I. Wikipedia

Aero Ae-45.label: Aero Ae-45
Aero Ae-45.description: The Aero 45 was a twin piston-engined civil utility aircraft produced in Czechoslovakia after World War II. It was the first product of the nation's post-war aviation industry and proved a great success, with many of the 590 produced being exported. Wikipedia

Aero L-29 Delfín.label: Aero L-29 Delfín
Aero L-29 Delfín.description: The Aero L-29 Delfín is a military jet trainer aircraft that became the standard jet trainer for the air forces of Warsaw Pact nations in the 1960s. It was Czechoslovakia's first locally designed and built jet aircraft. Wikipedia

Aichi B7A.label: Aichi B7A
Aichi B7A.description: The Aichi B7A Ryusei was a large and powerful carrier-borne torpedo-dive bomber produced by Aichi Kokuki KK for the Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service during the Second World War. Wikipedia

Aichi D1A.label: Aichi D1A
Aichi D1A.description: The Aichi D1A or Navy Type 94/96 Carrier Bomber was a Japanese carrier-based dive bomber of the 1930s. Wikipedia

Aichi D3A.label: Aichi D3A
Aichi D3A.description: The Aichi D3A, was a World War II carrier-borne dive bomber of the Imperial Japanese Navy. It was the primary dive bomber in the Imperial Japanese Navy, and participated in almost all actions, including the attack on Pearl Harbor. Wikipedia

Aichi E13A.label: Aichi E13A
Aichi E13A.description: The Aichi E13A was a long-range reconnaissance seaplane used by the Imperial Japanese Navy from 1941 to 1945. Numerically the most important floatplane of the IJN, it could carry a crew of three and a bombload of 250 kg. Wikipedia

Aero Spacelines Super Guppy.label: Aero Spacelines Super Guppy
Aero Spacelines Super Guppy.description: The Aero Spacelines Super Guppy is a large, wide-bodied cargo aircraft that is used for hauling outsized cargo components. It was the successor to the Pregnant Guppy, the first of the Guppy aircraft produced by Aero Spacelines. Wikipedia

Aichi E11A.label: Aichi E11A
Aichi E11A.description: The Aichi E11A was an Imperial Japanese Navy flying boat used during the first year of World War II for maritime patrol duties. The Allied reporting name for the type was "Laura"; the Japanese Navy designation was "Type 98 Reconnaissance Seaplane". Wikipedia

Aichi H9A.label: Aichi H9A
Aichi H9A.description: The Aichi H9A was an Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service flying boat used during the first years of World War II for crew training. Wikipedia

Aichi M6A.label: Aichi M6A1
Aichi M6A.description: The Aichi M6A Seiran was a submarine-launched attack floatplane designed for the Imperial Japanese Navy during World War II. Wikipedia

Airbus A310 MRTT.label: Airbus A310 MRTT
Airbus A310 MRTT.description: The Airbus A310 Multi Role Tanker Transport is an aerial refueling tanker aircraft based on the civilian Airbus A310. Previously, the A310 has been operated as a pure transport aircraft. Wikipedia

Airbus A330 MRTT.label: Airbus A330 MRTT
Airbus A330 MRTT.description: The Airbus A330 Multi Role Tanker Transport is an aerial refuelling tanker aircraft based on the civilian Airbus Airbus A330. Wikipedia

Aichi E16A.label: Aichi E16A
Aichi E16A.description: The Aichi E16A Zuiun was a two-seat reconnaissance seaplane operated by the Imperial Japanese Navy during World War II. Wikipedia

Airbus A400M.label: Airbus A400M Atlas
Airbus A400M.description: The Airbus A400M Atlas is a multi-national four-engine turboprop military transport aircraft. It was designed by Airbus Military as a tactical airlifter with strategic capabilities. Wikipedia

Airbus CC-150 Polaris.label: Airbus CC-150 Polaris
Airbus CC-150 Polaris.description: The Airbus CC-150 Polaris is the designation for the civilian Airbus A310-300s which have been converted for use as the primary long distance transport aircraft for the Royal Canadian Air Force. Wikipedia

Airco DH.1.label: Airco DH.1
Airco DH.1.description: The Airco DH.1 was an early military biplane of typical "Farman" pattern flown by Britain's Royal Flying Corps during World War I. Wikipedia

Airco DH.4.label: Airco DH.4
Airco DH.4.description: The Airco DH.4 was a British two-seat biplane day-bomber of the First World War. It was designed by Geoffrey de Havilland for Airco, and was the first British two seat light day-bomber to have an effective defensive armament. Wikipedia

Airspeed Oxford.label: Airspeed Oxford
Airspeed Oxford.description: The Airspeed AS.10 Oxford was a twin-engine aircraft used for training British Commonwealth aircrews in navigation, radio-operating, bombing and gunnery during the Second World War. Wikipedia

Airco DH.2.label: Airco DH.2
Airco DH.2.description: The Airco DH.2 was a single-seat biplane "pusher" aircraft which operated as a fighter during the First World War. It was the second pusher design by Geoffrey de Havilland for Airco, based on his earlier DH.1 two-seater. Wikipedia

Airco DH.9.label: Airco DH.9
Airco DH.9.description: The Airco DH.9 - also known after 1920 as the de Havilland DH.9 - was a British bomber used in the First World War. Wikipedia

Albatros C.III.label: Albatros C.III
Albatros C.III.description: The Albatros C.III was a German two-seat general-purpose biplane of World War I, built by Albatros Flugzeugwerke. Wikipedia

Albatros D.III.label: Albatros D.III
Albatros D.III.description: The Albatros D.III was a biplane fighter aircraft used by the Imperial German Army Air Service and the Austro-Hungarian Air Service during World War I. Wikipedia

Amiot 143.label: Amiot 143
Amiot 143.description: The Amiot 143M was a late 1930s French medium bomber designed to meet 1928 specifications for a bomber capable of day/night bombing, long-range reconnaissance and bomber escort. Wikipedia

Amiot 354.label: Amiot 354
Amiot 354.description: The Amiot 354 was the latest in a series of fast, twin-engine bombers which fought with the Armée de l'Air in limited numbers during the Battle of France. Wikipedia

Anatra DS.label: Anatra DS
Anatra DS.description: The Anatra DS or Anasal was a two-seat reconnaissance aircraft developed from the Anatra D. It was built in the Anatra factory in Odessa in the Russian Empire and flown during World War I and by both sides during the Russian Civil War. Wikipedia

Arado W 2.label: Arado W 2
Arado W 2.description: The Arado W 2 was a two-seat twin-engine seaplane trainer developed for the DVS in 1928. It was a cantilever monoplane with a fabric-covered steel tube fuselage that accommodated the pilot and instructor in tandem open cockpits. Wikipedia

Armstrong Whitworth AW.660 Argosy.label: Armstrong Whitworth AW.660 Argosy
Armstrong Whitworth AW.660 Argosy.description: The Armstrong Whitworth Argosy was a British post-war military transport/cargo aircraft and was the last aircraft produced by Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft. Wikipedia

Atlas Oryx.label: Atlas Oryx
Atlas Oryx.description: The Atlas Oryx is a medium-sized utility helicopter manufactured by the Atlas Aircraft Corporation of South Africa. Wikipedia

Avia B-135.label: Avia B-135
Avia B-135.description: The Avia B.135 was a Czechoslovak cantilever monoplane fighter aircraft. It was the production version of the Avia B.35 developed shortly before the war, based on the B.35/3 prototype but featuring a new all-metal wing. Wikipedia

Avia B-534.label: Avia B-534
Avia B-534.description: The Avia B-534 is a Czechoslovak biplane produced during the period between the Great War and World War II. Wikipedia

Avia B.122.label: Avia B.122
Avia B.122.description: The Avia B.122 Vosa was a Czechoslovak single-seat biplane trainer aircraft, which was developed in the mid-1930s. It saw some service in the first years of World War II. Wikipedia

Avia B.35.label: Avia B.35
Avia B.35.description: The Avia B.35 was a fighter aircraft built in Czechoslovakia shortly before World War II. It was designed to meet a 1935 requirement by the Czechoslovakian Air Force for a replacement for their B-534 fighter biplanes. Wikipedia

Avia BH-21.label: Avia BH-21
Avia BH-21.description: The Avia BH-21, first built in 1925, was a robust biplane that served an important role in securing Czechoslovak national security during the period between World War I and World War II. Wikipedia

Avia BH-25.label: Avia BH-25
Avia BH-25.description: The Avia BH-25 was a biplane airliner built in Czechoslovakia in 1926. Typical of airliners of its time, it seated five passengers within its fuselage, while the pilots sat in an open cockpit above. Wikipedia

Avia BH-3.label: Avia BH-3
Avia BH-3.description: The Avia BH-3 was a fighter plane built in Czechoslovakia in 1921. Conceptually a descendant of the BH-1 sports plane, it was a braced, low-wing monoplane of conventional configuration and tailskid undercarriage. Wikipedia

Avia BH-33.label: Avia BH-33
Avia BH-33.description: The Avia BH-33 was a biplane fighter aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in 1927. It was based on the BH-21J that demonstrated promising results by marrying the original BH-21 airframe with a licence-built Bristol Jupiter radial engine. Wikipedia

Avia BH-5.label: Avia BH-5
Avia BH-5.description: The Avia BH-5 was a two-seat sport aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in 1923. It was based on the firm's experience with the BH-1 and shared that aircraft's basic design a low-wing, braced monoplane. Wikipedia

Avia BH-6.label: Avia BH-6
Avia BH-6.description: The Avia BH-6 was a prototype fighter aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in 1923. It was a single-bay biplane of unusual configuration developed in tandem with the BH-7, which shared its fuselage and tail design. Wikipedia

Avia BH-7.label: Avia BH-7
Avia BH-7.description: The Avia BH-7 was a prototype fighter aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in 1923. It was a parasol-wing monoplane developed in tandem with and as an alternative to the BH-6, which shared its fuselage and tail design. Wikipedia

Avia BH-9.label: Avia BH-9
Avia BH-9.description: The Avia BH-9 was a one-seat sport aircraft built in Czechoslovakia in 1923, based on the BH-5. As with other developments in the BH-1 lineage, the BH-9 was a low-wing braced monoplane that accommodated ... Wikipedia

Aviation Traders Carvair.label: Aviation Traders Carvair
Aviation Traders Carvair.description: The Aviation Traders ATL-98 Carvair was a large piston four-engined transport aircraft. It was a Douglas DC-4-based air ferry developed by Freddie Laker's Aviation Traders Limited, with a capacity of 25 passengers and five cars, loaded at the front. Wikipedia

Avro 531 Spider.label: Avro 531 Spider
Avro 531 Spider.description: The Avro 531 Spider was a British fighter aircraft built by Avro during the First World War. It did not proceed past the prototype stage. Wikipedia

Avro Anson.label: Avro Anson
Avro Anson.description: The Avro Anson was a British twin-engined, multi-role aircraft that served with the Royal Air Force, Fleet Air Arm, Royal Canadian Air Force and numerous other air forces before, during, and after the Second World War. Wikipedia

Avro Antelope.label: Avro Antelope
Avro Antelope.description: The Avro 604 Antelope was a British light bomber which was designed and built in the late 1920s to meet a requirement for a light bomber to equip the Royal Air Force, competing against the Hawker Hart and the Fairey Fox II. Wikipedia

Avro Avian.label: Avro Avian
Avro Avian.description: The Avro Avian was a series of British light aircraft designed and built by Avro in the 1920s and '30s. While the various versions of the Avian were sound aircraft, they were comprehensively outsold by the de Havilland Moth and its descendants. Wikipedia

Avro Baby.label: Avro Baby
Avro Baby.description: The Avro 534 Baby was a British single-seat light sporting biplane built shortly after the First World War. Wikipedia

Avro Bison.label: Avro Bison
Avro Bison.description: The Avro 555 Bison was a British single-engined fleet spotter/reconnaissance aircraft built by Avro. Wikipedia

Avro Canada VZ-9 Avrocar.label: Avro Canada VZ-9 Avrocar
Avro Canada VZ-9 Avrocar.description: The Avro Canada VZ-9 Avrocar was a VTOL aircraft developed by Avro Aircraft Ltd. as part of a secret U.S. military project carried out in the early years of the Cold War. Wikipedia

Avro Lancaster.label: Avro Lancaster
Avro Lancaster.description: The Avro Lancaster is a British four-engined Second World War heavy bomber designed and built by Avro for the Royal Air Force. Wikipedia

Avro Manchester.label: Avro Manchester
Avro Manchester.description: The Avro 679 Manchester was a British twin-engine heavy bomber developed during the Second World War by the Avro aircraft company in the United Kingdom. Wikipedia

Avro Shackleton.label: Avro Shackleton
Avro Shackleton.description: The Avro Shackleton was a British long-range maritime patrol aircraft for use by the Royal Air Force and the South African Air Force. It was developed by Avro from the Avro Lincoln bomber. Wikipedia

Avro Tudor.label: Avro Tudor
Avro Tudor.description: Avro's Type 688 Tudor was a British piston-engined airliner based on their four-engine Lincoln bomber, itself a descendant of the famous Lancaster heavy bomber, and was Britain's first pressurised airliner. Wikipedia

Avro Tutor.label: Avro Tutor
Avro Tutor.description: A.V. Roe's Type 621 Tutor was a two-seat British radial-engined biplane from the interwar period. It was a simple but rugged initial trainer that was used by the Royal Air Force as well as many other air arms worldwide. Wikipedia

Avro York.label: Avro York
Avro York.description: The Avro York was a British transport aircraft that was derived from the Second World War Lancaster heavy bomber, and used in both military and civilian roles between 1943 and 1964. Wikipedia

BAC TSR-2.label: BAC TSR-2
BAC TSR-2.description: The British Aircraft Corporation TSR-2 was a cancelled Cold War strike and reconnaissance aircraft developed by the British Aircraft Corporation for the Royal Air Force in the late 1950s and early 1960s. Wikipedia

Baade 152.label: Baade 152
Baade 152.description: The Baade 152 also known as Dresden 152, VL-DDR 152 or simply 152 was the first German jet passenger airliner. It was built and tested in Dresden between 1956 and 1961, but failed to enter service. Wikipedia

Bartini Beriev VVA-14.label: Bartini Beriev VVA-14
Bartini Beriev VVA-14.description: The Bartini Beriev VVA-14 Vertikal`no-Vzletayuschaya Amphibia was developed in the Soviet Union during the 1970s. Wikipedia

Bede BD-5.label: Bede BD-5
Bede BD-5.description: The BD-5 Micro is a series of small, single-seat homebuilt aircraft created in the late 1960s by US aircraft designer Jim Bede and introduced to the market primarily in "kit" form by the now-defunct Bede Aircraft Corporation in the early 1970s. Wikipedia

Beechcraft Baron.label: Beechcraft Baron
Beechcraft Baron.description: The Beechcraft Baron is a light, twin-engined piston aircraft developed by Beechcraft. The Baron is a variant of the Travel Air, and was introduced in 1961. Wikipedia

Beechcraft Model 99.label: Beechcraft Model 99
Beechcraft Model 99.description: The Beechcraft Model 99 is a civilian aircraft produced by the Beechcraft. It is also known as the Beech 99 Airliner and the Commuter 99. Wikipedia

Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey.label: Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey
Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey.description: The Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey is an American multi-mission, military, tiltrotor aircraft with both a vertical takeoff and landing, and short takeoff and landing capability. Wikipedia

Beechcraft King Air.label: Beechcraft King Air
Beechcraft King Air.description: The Beechcraft King Air family is part of a line of twin-turboprop aircraft produced by Beechcraft. The King Air line comprises a number of models that have been divided into two families; the Model 90 ... Wikipedia

Beechcraft T-6 Texan II.label: Beechcraft T-6 Texan II
Beechcraft T-6 Texan II.description: The Beechcraft T-6 Texan II is a single-engined turboprop aircraft built by the Raytheon Aircraft Company. Wikipedia

Bell UH-1 Iroquois.label: Bell UH-1 Iroquois
Bell UH-1 Iroquois.description: The Bell UH-1 Iroquois is a military helicopter powered by a single, turboshaft engine, with a two-bladed main rotor and tail rotor. Wikipedia

Bell X-16.label: Bell X-16
Bell X-16.description: The Bell X-16 was a high altitude reconnaissance jet aircraft designed in the United States in the 1950s. A mock-up of the X-16 was built, but the project was cancelled in favor of the Martin RB-57 before any X-16 aircraft were completed. Wikipedia

Bell X-14.label: Bell X-14
Bell X-14.description: The Bell X-14 was an experimental VTOL aircraft flown in the United States in the 1950s. The main objective of the project was to demonstrate horizontal and vertical takeoff, hover, transition to forward flight, and vertical landing. Wikipedia

Bell XFL Airabonita.label: Bell XFL Airabonita
Bell XFL Airabonita.description: The Bell XFL Airabonita was a United States experimental shipboard interceptor aircraft developed for the United States Navy by Bell Aircraft. Wikipedia
